"{\n  \"text\": \"Hi everybody. One of the problems I think that's occurring in our modern world is that our waste, our organic waste is mixed with a lot of decay-resistant waste like plastics and other chemicals that don't easily break down. And what this is causing is a decay-resistant sludge that doesn't break down over long periods of time. It just kind of sits there. And that's our landfills, the way we process our sewage and other things leave products that can't be dealt with. They leave areas of land that can't be dealt with. These areas become toxic because the biology that is needed all over the world, all over the earth, to churn the carbon chains into new carbon chains that are then reused in the life of and the process and the decay cycle all flowing through is interrupted because the decay cycle is so stifled. Because we're creating areas where decay just can't occur. There's too much anaerobic uh compaction. There's too many toxic substances in there. And also the good organic salts and organic matter that we could use that the world could churn back into it, is so compacted and sludged up that it's not broken down and the organic matter gets wasted in there in this decay resistant zone that we create. And what we need to do is as opposed to taking all that waste and putting it in one place, the idea behind the waste is to spread it out. Now, of course, you want to take out the plastics and things like that, but the good nitrogen-rich organic waste that we just throw away is valuable stuff because it purifies the dirty organic matter that's on the land that we've already created. By putting nitrogen-rich humus by capturing that nitrogen in our waste, we give nature a way of churning out the organic matter which purifies it, which drops away impurities, which creates good carbon chains, which are then used for cleaner, more effective life that is healthy, that fights against the decay cycle, that has, as its inheritance, health. And so what we need to be doing is changing not just the way we're doing agriculture, but the way we're dealing with our waste. Our waste needs to be preserved in a way that we're not using it now. Biosolids are a great example of this. This is sewage that we take and we put it into very compacted pellets. You know, we we take it, we process it down, we take the water out, we uh we take it and we put it into these very dense pellets, and we say, okay, now it's processed. But what we've done is we've compacted all that organic matter into such a way that wherever we put it, it's gonna be toxic because the the salt levels are too high in it. So wherever it starts to dissolve and break down, it's going to put those high salt levels someplace else. A lot of those salts are valuable and they could be used by nature, but not in the concentrations that we put them. And the thing is, we could just break down the waste and start to disperse the waste as we get it, spread it out over large areas where it is properly digested, where the waste is actually dealt with, but instead we just concentrate it. And that's like giving, that's like sending a little note, a little package to the future with a card that says, fuck you. Anyway, I just want to make a video about that. Thanks, y'all.\",\n  \"sentences\": [\n    {\n      \"text\": \" Hi everybody.\",\n      \"start\": 0.56,\n      \"end\": 1.68,\n      \"duration\": 1.12,\n      \"confidence\": 0.985,\n      \"tokens\": [\n        {\n          \"text\": \" Hi\",\n          \"start\": 0.56,\n          \"end\": 0.88,\n          \"duration\": 0.32,\n          \"confidence\": 0.989\n        },\n        {\n          \"text\": \" ever\",\n          \"start\": 0.96,\n          \"end\": 1.12,\n          \"duration\": 0.16,\n          \"confidence\": 1.0\n        },\n        {\n          \"text\": \"yb\",\n          \"start\": 1.12,\n          \"end\": 1.36,\n          \"duration\": 0.24,\n          \"confidence\": 1.0\n        },\n        {\n          \"text